Abby Marshall.label: Abby Marshall
Abby Marshall.description: Abby Marshall is a chess player from Columbus, Ohio, USA, who has resided in Virginia, USA since late 2005. Wikipedia

Aleksander Wojtkiewicz.label: Aleksander Wojtkiewicz
Aleksander Wojtkiewicz.description: Aleksander Wojtkiewicz was a Polish chess grandmaster. He was born in Latvia. In his early teens he was already a strong player; a student of ex-world champion Mikhail Tal whom he assisted in the 1979 Interzonal tournament in Riga. Wikipedia

Alex Yermolinsky.label: Alex Yermolinsky
Alex Yermolinsky.description: Alex Yermolinsky is an American chess Grandmaster. In 1993, Yermolinsky won the U.S. Chess Championship, tying for first place with Alexander Shabalov. In 1996 he was the sole champion. Wikipedia

Alexander Goldin.label: Ear Nose & Throat Goldin Alexander D MD

Alexander Onischuk.label: Alexander Onischuk
Alexander Onischuk.description:
Alexander Onischuk is a Soviet-born American chess grandmaster.
Originally from Ukraine, he immigrated to the United States in 2001. He was the 2006 U.S. Chess Champion. Wikipedia

Alexander Shabalov.label: Alexander Shabalov
Alexander Shabalov.description: Alexander Shabalov is an American chess grandmaster. He is a four-time winner of the United States Chess Championship, with his most recent title coming in 2007. Wikipedia

Andrew Soltis.label: Andrew Soltis
Andrew Soltis.description:
Andrew Eden Soltis is a chess Grandmaster, author and columnist.
He won at Reggio Emilia 1971–72 and was equal first at the 1977 U.S. Open Championship in New York. Wikipedia

Anna Hahn (chess player).label: Anna Hahn
Anna Hahn (chess player).description:
Anna Hahn is an American chess player with the title of Woman International Master.
In her native Latvia, she took the women's championship of 1992 and then moved to the U.S., where in 1994 she won the ... Wikipedia

Anna Zatonskih.label: Anna Zatonskih
Anna Zatonskih.description: Anna Zatonskih is a chess player from the United States. She is a Woman Grandmaster, as well as an International Master. She is a chess professional, who coaches players and competes in tournaments. Wikipedia

Boris Kreiman.label: Boris Kreiman
Boris Kreiman.description: Boris Kreiman is an American Grandmaster of chess. Kreiman a 3rd place winner in a U.S. Chess Championship in Seattle is also a winner of the Frank P. Samford, Jr. Chess Fellowship. Wikipedia

Danny Kopec.label: Danny Kopec
Danny Kopec.description: Danny Kopec is a chess International Master, author, and computer science professor at Brooklyn College. He graduated from Dartmouth College in the class of 1975. Kopec later received a PhD in Machine Intelligence from the University of Edinburgh. Wikipedia
Books: Chess World Title Contenders and Their Styles

Elena Donaldson-Akhmilovskaya.label: Elena Donaldson-Akhmilovskaya
Elena Donaldson-Akhmilovskaya.description: Elena Donaldson-Akhmilovskaya was a Woman Grandmaster of chess. She has been one of the strongest woman players in the world. Wikipedia

Eugene Perelshteyn.label: Eugene Perelshteyn
Eugene Perelshteyn.description: Eugene Perelshteyn is a chess grandmaster and author. He earned the International Master title in 2001 and the Grandmaster title in 2006. He won the U.S. Junior Closed Championship in 2000. Wikipedia

Gata Kamsky.label: Gata Kamsky
Gata Kamsky.description: Gata Kamsky is a Soviet-born American chess grandmaster, and a former World Rapid Chess Champion. As of May 2012, he was rated No. 2 in the United States and No. 14 in the world. Wikipedia

George H. D. Gossip.label: George H. D. Gossip
George H. D. Gossip.description: George Hatfeild Dingley Gossip was a minor American-English chess master and writer. He competed in chess tournaments between 1870 and 1895, playing against most of the world's leading players, but with only modest success. The writer G. H. Wikipedia
George H. D. Gossip.Born: December 6, 1841, New York City, New York, United States

George Henry Mackenzie.label: George Henry Mackenzie
George Henry Mackenzie.description: George Henry Mackenzie was a Scottish-American chess master. Wikipedia
George Henry Mackenzie.Died: April 14, 1891, New York City, New York, United States

Harry Nelson Pillsbury.label: Harry Nelson Pillsbury
Harry Nelson Pillsbury.description: Harry Nelson Pillsbury was a leading chess player. At age 22, he won one of the strongest tournaments of the time but his illness and early death prevented him from challenging for the World Chess Championship. Wikipedia

Henry Ernest Atkins.label: Henry Ernest Atkins
Henry Ernest Atkins.description: Henry Ernest Atkins was a British chess master who is best known for his unparalleled record of winning the British Chess Championship nine times in eleven attempts. He won every year from 1905 to 1911, and again in 1924 and 1925. Wikipedia

Henry Hosmer.label: Henry Hosmer
Henry Hosmer.description: Henry Hosmer was a nineteenth-century American chess master. He is known to have played in only two significant chess tournaments the Second and Third American Chess Congresses in 1871 and 1874. Wikipedia

Ildar Ibragimov.label: Ildar Ibragimov
Ildar Ibragimov.description:
Ildar Ibragimov is a chess Grandmaster. He played on the bronze-medal-winning USA team in the 2006 Chess Olympiad.
Born in Kazan, Russia, he was equal first alongside Kramnik and Kharlov at the 1991 USSR Under 26 Championship. Wikipedia

Hikaru Nakamura.label: Hikaru Nakamura
Hikaru Nakamura.description: Hikaru Nakamura is an American chess grandmaster. He is ranked No. 7 in the world by FIDE on the February 2014 rankings and is a three-time United States Chess Champion. Wikipedia

Igor Vasilyevich Ivanov.label: Igor Vasilyevich Ivanov
Igor Vasilyevich Ivanov.description: Igor Vasilyevich Ivanov was a Russian-born Canadian Grandmaster of chess and a concert pianist. Wikipedia
Igor Vasilyevich Ivanov.Died: November 17, 2005, St. George, Utah, United States

James A. Leonard.label: James A. Leonard
James A. Leonard.description: James A. Leonard was a young American chess master, who grew up as a son of poor Irish immigrants in New York City. He learned to play chess at age 16 or 17. Wikipedia

Hugh Myers.label: Hugh Myers
Hugh Myers.description: Hugh Edward Myers was an American chess master and author. He won or tied for first in the state chess championships of Illinois, Wisconsin, Missouri, and Iowa, as well as the USCF Region VIII championship. Wikipedia

Jaan Ehlvest.label: Jaan Ehlvest
Jaan Ehlvest.description: Jaan Ehlvest is a chess player, who was awarded the title of Grandmaster by FIDE in 1987 and was named Estonian sportsman of the year in 1987 and 1989. Since 2006, he has represented the United States. Wikipedia

James Grundy (chess player).label: James Grundy
James Grundy (chess player).description: James Glover Grundy was an English-American chess master. Wikipedia

John Curdo.label: John Curdo
John Curdo.description: John A. Curdo is an American chess player from Auburn, Massachusetts, best known for winning the Massachusetts state championship 17 times between 1948 and 1985, as well as the US Senior Championship. Wikipedia

Jesse Kraai.label: Jesse Kraai
Jesse Kraai.description: Jesse Kraai is a chess Grandmaster living in Richmond, CA. Kraai reached GM status in 2007. He was the first American-born player to achieve the title since Tal Shaked in 1997. Wikipedia

John Fedorowicz.label: John Fedorowicz
John Fedorowicz.description: John Peter Fedorowicz from the Bronx area of New York is an American International Grandmaster of chess, and a chess writer. Wikipedia
John Fedorowicz.Born: September 27, 1958 (age 55), New York City, New York, United States

Kayden Troff.label: Kayden Troff
Kayden Troff.description: Kayden William Troff is the current Under 14 World Youth chess champion, after a gold-medal finish at the World Youth Chess Championships in Maribor, Slovenia, in November 2012. Wikipedia

John Washington Baird.label: John Washington Baird
John Washington Baird.description: John Washington Baird was a minor American chess master, who played in a number of American and international chess tournaments between 1880 and 1906. He was the brother of David Graham Baird, who was also an American chess master. Wikipedia

Maurice Ashley.label: Maurice Ashley
Maurice Ashley.description: Maurice Ashley is a chess grandmaster, author, commentator, app designer, puzzle inventor, and motivational speaker. He is currently a Joint Fellow at the Berkman Center at Harvard and the Media Lab at MIT. Wikipedia

Larry Evans.label: Larry Evans
Larry Evans.description: Larry Melvyn Evans was an American chess grandmaster, author, and journalist. He won or shared the U.S. Chess Championship five times and the U.S. Open Chess Championship four times. Wikipedia
Larry Evans.Born: March 22, 1932, New York City, New York, United States

Melikset Khachiyan.label: Melikset Khachiyan
Melikset Khachiyan.description:
Melikset Khachiyan is an Armenian-American Grandmaster of chess, originally from Azerbaijan, who now resides in Los Angeles.
Khachiyan began playing chess at the age of eight. Two years later he won the Baku Junior Championship. Wikipedia

Nicholas Nip.label: Nicholas Nip
Nicholas Nip.description: Nicholas Nip is a United States Chess Federation National Master. In 2008, he became the youngest USCF Master in history, obtaining a rating of 2207 at the age of 9 years, 11 months and 26 days, a record that was surpassed in 2010 by Samuel Sevian. Wikipedia

Nick de Firmian.label: Nick de Firmian
Nick de Firmian.description: Nicholas Ernest de Firmian, is a chess grandmaster and three-time U.S. chess champion, winning in 1987, 1995, and 1998. He also tied for first in 2002, but Larry Christiansen won the playoff. Wikipedia

Nicolas Rossolimo.label: Nicolas Rossolimo
Nicolas Rossolimo.description: Nicolas Rossolimo was an American-French-Russian-Greek chess Grandmaster. He was many times champion of Paris, France, and after relocating to the United States won the 1955 U.S. Open Championship. Wikipedia
Nicolas Rossolimo.Died: July 24, 1975, New York City, New York, United States

Pal Benko.label: Pal Benko
Pal Benko.description: Pal Benko is a chess grandmaster, author, and composer of endgame studies and chess problems. Wikipedia

Napoleon Marache.label: Napoleon Marache
Napoleon Marache.description: Napoleon Marache was born in France and moved to the United States at about age 12. He learned the game of chess around 1844, and immediately became a devotee. He began composing chess problems and writing about chess the following year. Wikipedia
Napoleon Marache.Died: May 11, 1875, New York City, New York, United States

Ray Robson.label: Ray Robson
Ray Robson.description: Ray Robson is an American chess player who holds the title of Grandmaster. In October 2009, about two weeks before turning 15, he became the youngest grandmaster-elect in history who plays for the United States. Wikipedia

Paul Felix Schmidt.label: Paul Felix Schmidt
Paul Felix Schmidt.description: Paul Felix Schmidt was an Estonian chess International Master, chess writer, and chemist. Wikipedia

Robert Hess (chess player).label: Robert Hess
Robert Hess (chess player).description: Robert Lee Hess is an American chess Grandmaster. In May 2012, his FIDE rating was 2635, fifth in the United States. Wikipedia

Sonja Graf.label: Sonja Graf
Sonja Graf.description: Sonja Graf was a German chess master who also lived in Argentina and the United States. She was the Women's World Sub-Champion, two-time winner of the U.S. Women's Chess Championship and author of two ... Wikipedia
Sonja Graf.Died: March 6, 1965, New York City, New York, United States

Roman Dzindzichashvili.label: Roman Dzindzichashvili
Roman Dzindzichashvili.description: Roman Yakovlevich Dzindzichashvili is a chess Grandmaster. Wikipedia

Tatev Abrahamyan.label: Tatev Abrahamyan
Tatev Abrahamyan.description: Tatev Abrahamyan is one of the youngest top-rated U.S. women's chess players, along with Alisa Melekhina, Sabina Foisor, and Abby Marshall. Wikipedia

Tunç Hamarat.label: Tunç Hamarat
Tunç Hamarat.description: Tunç Hamarat is a Turkish chess player living in Austria and the sixteenth ICCF World Champion, 1999–2004. Wikipedia

Victor Palciauskas.label: Victor Palciauskas
Victor Palciauskas.description: Dr Victor Palciauskas is an American International Correspondence Chess Grandmaster, most famous for being the tenth ICCF World Champion, 1978–84. Wikipedia

Varuzhan Akobian.label: Varuzhan Akobian
Varuzhan Akobian.description: Varuzhan Akobian is an Armenian-born American chess grandmaster. Originally from Armenia, he now resides in Los Angeles. He played on the bronze-medal-winning U.S. team in the 2006 and 2008 Chess Olympiads. Wikipedia

Walter Browne.label: Walter Browne
Walter Browne.description: Walter Shawn Browne is an American chess Grandmaster and poker player. Browne has won the U.S. Chess Championship six times. Wikipedia

Vinay Bhat.label: Vinay Bhat
Vinay Bhat.description: Vinay Bhat is an American chess Grandmaster. Bhat earned his third Grandmaster norm in July 2007 at the age of 23, though he did not obtain the Grandmaster title immediately due to rating requirements. Wikipedia
Vinay Bhat.Born: June 4, 1984 (age 29), Santa Clara, California, United States

Weaver W. Adams.label: Weaver W. Adams
Weaver W. Adams.description: Weaver Warren Adams was an American chess master, author, and opening theoretician. His greatest competitive achievement was winning the U.S. Open Championship in 1948. He played in the U.S. Championship five times. Wikipedia
Weaver W. Adams.Died: January 6, 1963, Cedar Grove, New Jersey, United States

William John Donaldson.label: William John Donaldson
William John Donaldson.description: William John Donaldson is an International Master of chess. He has been an IM since 1983. He is also an author, organizer, journalist and chess politician. Wikipedia
William John Donaldson.Born: September 24, 1958 (age 55), Los Angeles, California, United States

William Lombardy.label: William Lombardy
William Lombardy.description: William James Lombardy is an American chess grandmaster, chess writer, teacher, and a former Catholic priest. Wikipedia
William Lombardy.Born: December 4, 1937 (age 76), New York City, New York, United States
Books: Chess for Children Step by Step A New
Easy Way to Learn the Game

William H.K. Pollock.label: William H. K. Pollock
William H.K. Pollock.description:
William Henry Krause Pollock was an English chess master, and a surgeon.
Pollock was born in Cheltenham, England, the son of the Rev. William J. Pollock. He was educated at Clifton College. Wikipedia

Frank Marshall (chess player).label: Frank Marshall
Frank Marshall (chess player).description: Frank James Marshall was the U.S. Chess Champion from 1909 to 1936, and one of the world's strongest chess players in the early part of the 20th century. Wikipedia
Frank Marshall (chess player).Born: August 10, 1877, New York City, New York, United States
Frank Marshall (chess player).Died: November 9, 1944, Jersey City, New Jersey, United States

Gerardo Barbero.label: Gerardo Barbero
Gerardo Barbero.description:
Gerardo Barbero was an Argentine chess grandmaster. He was born in Lanús, Buenos Aires, and raised in Rosario, Santa Fe.
Barbero came fifth in the World Junior Chess Championship of 1978. Wikipedia

Rudolf Spielmann.label: Rudolf Spielmann
Rudolf Spielmann.description: Rudolf Spielmann was an Austrian-Jewish chess player of the romantic school, and chess writer. Wikipedia

Reuben Fine.label: Reuben Fine
Reuben Fine.description: Reuben Fine was an American chess grandmaster, psychologist, university professor, and author of many books on both chess and psychology. He was one of the strongest chess players in the world from the late 1930s into the early 1950s. Wikipedia
Reuben Fine.Born: October 11, 1914, New York City, New York, United States
Reuben Fine.Died: March 26, 1993, New York City, New York, United States

Evgeny Alekseev (chess player).label: Evgeny Alekseev
Evgeny Alekseev (chess player).description: Evgeny Vladimirovich Alekseev is a Russian chess grandmaster. In 2006 he won the Russian Chess Championship, defeating Dmitry Jakovenko in a playoff match. Wikipedia

Arvid Kubbel.label: Arvid Kubbel
Arvid Kubbel.description: Arvid Kubbel was a Russian chess player and composer of chess problems and endgame studies. He was a brother of Evgeny and Leonid Kubbel; their father was born in Latvia, of Baltic German descent. Wikipedia

Sergey Fedorchuk.label: Sergey Fedorchuk
Sergey Fedorchuk.description:
Sergey Fedorchuk is a Ukrainian chess grandmaster.
In 1995 he won the European Youth Chess Championship. In 2006 he won at rapid tournament held in Banyoles and tied for 1st–3rd with Gabriel Sargissian and Tigran L. Petrosian in the 8th Dubai Open. Wikipedia

Wang Rui (chess player).label: Wang Rui
Wang Rui (chess player).description: Wang Rui is a Chinese chess Grandmaster. Wikipedia

Giorgio Porreca.label: Giorgio Porreca
Giorgio Porreca.description:
Giorgio Porreca was an Italian chess player and International Master.
He won the Italian Chess Championship two times at Sorrento in 1950 and at Rovigo in 1956. Wikipedia

Miyoko Watai.label: Miyoko Watai
Miyoko Watai.description: Miyoko Watai is a Japanese women's chess champion, and the general secretary of the Japan Chess Association. She is a Woman International Master. She lives in the old Kamata ward, which is now part of Ōta, Tokyo. Wikipedia

Alexander Graf.label: Alexander Graf
Alexander Graf.description: Alexander Graf is an Uzbekistani-German chess grandmaster. In 2000 he moved to Germany and took his father's name. He took bronze in the 2003 European Individual Chess Championship. In 2004 he won the German Chess Championship. Wikipedia

Arkadij Naiditsch.label: Arkadij Naiditsch
Arkadij Naiditsch.description: Arkadij Naiditsch is a German chess Grandmaster who was the clear winner of the Dortmund Sparkassen 2005 Tournament, ahead of higher-rated and well-known players such as Loek van Wely, Veselin Topalov, ... Wikipedia

Eric Lobron.label: Eric Lobron
Eric Lobron.description: Eric Lobron is a German chess player of American descent. A former two-time national champion, he has been awarded the title Grandmaster by the World Chess Federation. Wikipedia
Eric Lobron.Born: May 7, 1960 (age 53), Germantown, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, United States

Hans-Joachim Hecht.label: Hans-Joachim Hecht
Hans-Joachim Hecht.description: Hans-Joachim Hecht is a German chess player and twice the national champion. His first name is often abbreviated to Hajo. Wikipedia

Helmut Pfleger.label: Helmut Pfleger
Helmut Pfleger.description: Helmut Pfleger is a German chess Grandmaster and author. He was one of the most promising chess players in the sixties and seventies. By profession, he is a doctor of medicine. Wikipedia

Hermann von Gottschall.label: Hermann von Gottschall
Hermann von Gottschall.description: Hermann von Gottschall was a German chess master, son of the poet Rudolf Gottschall who was also a noted chess player. Wikipedia

Hugo Süchting.label: Hugo Süchting
Hugo Süchting.description:
Hugo Süchting was a German chess player.
He won at Kiel 1893 took 13th at Leipzig 1894, shared 2nd with Ignatz von Popiel, behind Robert Henry Barnes, at Eisenach 1896, and took 15th at Berlin 1897. Wikipedia

Jan Gustafsson.label: Jan Gustafsson
Jan Gustafsson.description:
Jan Gustafsson is a German grandmaster of chess.
He started playing in the chess club Hamburg SK, where he still continues to be a member. Wikipedia

Karsten Müller.label: Karsten Müller
Karsten Müller.description: Karsten Müller is a German chess Grandmaster and author. He earned the Grandmaster title in 1998 and a PhD in mathematics in 2002 at the University of Hamburg. Wikipedia

Klaus Bischoff.label: Klaus Bischoff
Klaus Bischoff.description:
Klaus Bischoff is a German chess player. He was awarded the Grandmaster title by FIDE in 1990.
In international tournaments, he has taken a share of first place on a number of occasions, including ... Wikipedia

Klaus Junge.label: Klaus Junge
Klaus Junge.description: Klaus Junge was one of the youngest German chess masters. Wikipedia

Max Lange.label: Max Lange
Max Lange.description: Max Lange was a German chess player and problem composer. Wikipedia

Rainer Knaak.label: Rainer Knaak
Rainer Knaak.description:
Rainer Fritz Albert Knaak is a German Chess Grandmaster.
He learned the game at the age of 5 from his father, Hans Knaak. Wikipedia

Predrag Nikolić.label: Predrag Nikolić
Predrag Nikolić.description:
Predrag Nikolić is a Bosnian chess grandmaster.
He first competed for the Yugoslav Championship in 1979, taking a share of second place. The following year and again in 1984, he went one step further and became the Yugoslav national champion. Wikipedia

Rustem Dautov.label: Rustem Dautov
Rustem Dautov.description:
Rustem Hazitovich Dautov is a German chess Grandmaster of Tatar origin.
In 1983 he won the USSR U18 youth championship and in 1986 the Belarusian Chess Championship. Wikipedia

Adriana Nikolova.label: Adriana Nikolova
Adriana Nikolova.description: Adriana Nikolova is a Bulgarian chess Woman Grandmaster. She is presently Bulgaria's newest WGM and her current chess club team is Lokomotiv 2000 from Plovdiv, with which she has won three national championships. Wikipedia

Jeff Sarwer.label: Jeff Sarwer
Jeff Sarwer.description: Jeff Sarwer is a Canadian Finnish former child chess prodigy whose charismatic personality and chess talent made him a well known media figure. Wikipedia

Timur Gareev.label: Timur Gareev
Timur Gareev.description: Timur Gareev is an American chess grandmaster. Gareev was a part of the University of Texas at Brownsville's chess team from August 2005 to August 2006 and from August 2009 to December 2011 where he ... Wikipedia
Education: University of Texas at Brownsville and Texas Southmost College

Wolfgang Uhlmann.label: Wolfgang Uhlmann
Wolfgang Uhlmann.description: Wolfgang Uhlmann is a prominent German International Grandmaster of chess. Despite being a dedicated professional chess player, and undoubtedly the GDR's most successful ever, he has also had a career in accountancy. Wikipedia

Wolfgang Unzicker.label: Wolfgang Unzicker
Wolfgang Unzicker.description: Wolfgang Unzicker was one of the strongest German chess Grandmasters from 1945 to about 1970. He decided against making chess his profession, choosing law instead. Wikipedia

Alexander Motylev.label: Alexander Motylev
Alexander Motylev.description:
Alexander Anatolyevich Motylev is a chess grandmaster, the current European champion and a former Russian champion.
He learnt how to play at the age of four and a half years and at age six took part in group instruction sessions. Wikipedia

Bogdan Lalić.label: Bogdan Lalić
Bogdan Lalić.description: Bogdan Lalic is a Croatian chess grandmaster. He was born in the former Yugoslavia in 1964. FIDE awarded him the International Grandmaster title in 1988. He finished equal first at the Pleven 1987 and Sarajevo 1988 tournaments. Wikipedia

Darmen Sadvakasov.label: Darmen Sadvakasov
Darmen Sadvakasov.description: Darmen Sadvakasov is a Kazakhstani chess grandmaster. Sadvakasov received the International Master title in 1995 and the GM title in 1998 as a result of his victory in the World Junior Championship. Wikipedia

David Howell (chess player).label: David Howell
David Howell (chess player).description: David Wei Liang Howell is an English chess Grandmaster and the current British Chess Champion. He is the youngest chess Grandmaster in the United Kingdom, a title he earned when he came second during ... Wikipedia

Dibyendu Barua.label: Dibyendu Barua
Dibyendu Barua.description: Dibyendu Barua is a chess Grandmaster from the city of Kolkata in the Indian state of West Bengal. He is the second Indian to become a Grandmaster, after Viswanathan Anand. Wikipedia

Eduardas Rozentalis.label: Eduardas Rozentalis
Eduardas Rozentalis.description:
Eduardas Rozentalis is a Lithuanian chess grandmaster.
He played for the Lithuanian team at first board in seven Chess Olympiads in 1992–98, and 2002–06.
In 1995 he tied for first in the Canadian Open Chess Championship. Wikipedia

Grigory Sanakoev.label: Grigory Sanakoev
Grigory Sanakoev.description:
Grigory Konstantinovich Sanakoev is a Russian International Correspondence Chess Grandmaster, most famous for being the twelfth ICCF World Champion, 1984–91.
He is the author of a book on correspondence chess World Champion at the Third Attempt. Wikipedia

Ivar Bern.label: Ivar Bern
Ivar Bern.description: Ivar Bern is a Norwegian chess player, most famous for being the seventeenth World Correspondence Chess Champion, 2002–07. In over-the-board chess he holds an International Master title. Wikipedia

Ioannis Nikolaidis.label: Ioannis Nikolaidis
Ioannis Nikolaidis.description:
Ioannis Nikolaidis is a Greek chess Grandmaster.
He won the Greek Chess Championship in 1995. and came third in the Balkan Individual Chess Championship of 2002 in Istanbul. Wikipedia

Jan Werle.label: Jan Werle
Jan Werle.description: Jan Werle is a Dutch chess player with the title Grandmaster. Wikipedia

Kiril Georgiev.label: Kiril Georgiev
Kiril Georgiev.description:
Kiril Dimitrov Georgiev is a Bulgarian chess grandmaster and three-time national champion.
Kiril Georgiev first caught the eye of the chess world in 1983, when he became the World Junior Champion with an unusually strong score of 11½ out of 13. Wikipedia
